        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1213139291" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7547361059674740949"> I initially listen to this on Librivox, and thought it was a very nice listen. Then I realised that there was a project Gutenberg read that went along with the audio. I read the book and also very much enjoyed that.<br/><br/>My favourite section was the description of the mountains and the ice. I could really imagine what this was like. I also liked how the relationship between the boy and the girl developed, and how the boy looked after the girl and how she trusted him and looked up to him so much.<br/><br/>When </span>
  <span id="freeText7547361059674740949" style="display:none"> I initially listen to this on Librivox, and thought it was a very nice listen. Then I realised that there was a project Gutenberg read that went along with the audio. I read the book and also very much enjoyed that.<br /><br />My favourite section was the description of the mountains and the ice. I could really imagine what this was like. I also liked how the relationship between the boy and the girl developed, and how the boy looked after the girl and how she trusted him and looked up to him so much.<br /><br />When I compared the Project Gutenberg translation with the one that shown here i.e. the one by Marianne Moore, I realise that there is a section that is missing at the beginning of the Gutenberg translation. That is, the section describing what Christmas is like in Germany and what happens on Christmas Eve and Christmas Day for the children. I knew a little bit about this already, so it didn't really matter that it was missing. But I don't understand whether it was there in the German original or not. Why would it need to be in a German original, since they would be the most likely people to understand about Christmas Eve and Christmas Day in Germany? So if it wasn't there in the original, where has it suddenly come from?<br /><br />I thought this was an extremely pleasant, quite moving story/fable/fairytale.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7547361059674740949" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
