<div id="review_908350194" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/908350194" />
    <a title="Stephen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/28086345-stephen"><img alt="Stephen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1396467487p2/28086345.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/908350194?book_show_action=true">Apr 12, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Stephen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Stephen" href="/user/show/28086345-stephen">Stephen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer908350194" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9835402073603328460">A great story, simple (even banal) at first glance but full of myth, allegory, and quiet mystery just under the surface. Two kids, &quot;the right road lost&quot; (in Dante&apos;s words), wander out onto a glacier in the Austrian Alps on <i>Heilige Nacht</i> (Christmas Eve). Taking refuge in a stone cave or hut, Conrad and Susanna are kept awake - and from freezing to death - by a vial of coffee extract given as a gift by their grandmother, then by a stirring and inexplicable light show over a vast ice field at midni</span>
  <span id="freeText9835402073603328460" style="display:none">A great story, simple (even banal) at first glance but full of myth, allegory, and quiet mystery just under the surface. Two kids, "the right road lost" (in Dante's words), wander out onto a glacier in the Austrian Alps on <i>Heilige Nacht</i> (Christmas Eve). Taking refuge in a stone cave or hut, Conrad and Susanna are kept awake - and from freezing to death - by a vial of coffee extract given as a gift by their grandmother, then by a stirring and inexplicable light show over a vast ice field at midnight, which the young girl sees as the coming of the Christ-child. On the night in which Christ, too, was born in a cave (not in a lean-to, with soft natural lighting, as most people believe) the lost children struggling to survive witness the utter beauty of Nature and Spirit.<br /><br />Undiluted magic here. A little slow to start (like a good walk or a long German sentence), but at 76 pages it's a quick, breathtaking read. Written in 1853 but translated at the end of World War II by the great American Modernist poet Marianne Moore, Stifter's <i>Rock Crystal</i> is a quiet, mystical story that reads like half-folktale, half-allegory of grace. Out on the ledge, in the most vulnerable place, we receive the small gift and the celestial fire that transforms our vision.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9835402073603328460" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


