<div id="review_1098125002" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1098125002" />
    <a title="Antonomasia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6249204-antonomasia"><img alt="Antonomasia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609885936p2/6249204.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1098125002?book_show_action=true">Nov 05, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Antonomasia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Antonomasia" href="/user/show/6249204-antonomasia">Antonomasia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook 9781908968760" href="/book/show/18918388-rock-crystal">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6249204-antonomasia?shelf=christmas">christmas</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6249204-antonomasia?shelf=19th-century">19th-century</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6249204-antonomasia?shelf=novella">novella</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6249204-antonomasia?shelf=scribd">scribd</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6249204-antonomasia?shelf=2015">2015</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6249204-antonomasia?shelf=central-eastern-europe">central-eastern-europe</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6249204-antonomasia?shelf=austro-hungarian">austro-hungarian</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1098125002" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1387477453164537799">[3.5] Set at Christmas, but have you <i>heard</i> this weather?<br/><br/>I can see why some people find <i>Rock Crystal</i> sweet, others cloying - I&apos;m midway. A piece somewhere between a short story and a novella, it&apos;s very Victorian (actually Austrian, pub.1845, this translation made 100 years later) and the mental gear-shift it required was the same as the first such I remember making when, as a kid, I read one of Andrew Lang&apos;s Fairy Books found at my grandmother&apos;s. <br/><br/>The two children, Conrad and Sanna, are impossibly</span>
  <span id="freeText1387477453164537799" style="display:none">[3.5] Set at Christmas, but have you <i>heard</i> this weather?<br /><br />I can see why some people find <i>Rock Crystal</i> sweet, others cloying - I'm midway. A piece somewhere between a short story and a novella, it's very Victorian (actually Austrian, pub.1845, this translation made 100 years later) and the mental gear-shift it required was the same as the first such I remember making when, as a kid, I read one of Andrew Lang's Fairy Books found at my grandmother's. <br /><br />The two children, Conrad and Sanna, are impossibly good, and of course appropriately so for their ages and genders. The chocolate-box village sounds lovely ... no-one's going to mention the less pleasant side of unchanging traditions and close-knit small community. The descriptions of scenery are very well done in their Victorian way, but can't compete with their more striking and vivid counterparts - which I can still feel - from another, more complicated, story of children lost in the snow, Tarjei Vesaas' <i>The Ice Palace</i>.<br /><br />Also, nice to know that 'Holy Night' (as in the carol Silent Night) is an Austrian / German name for the night between Christmas Eve &amp; Christmas Day.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1387477453164537799" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


