<div id="review_3372299680" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3372299680" />
    <a title="Brian Reynolds" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/30271885-brian-reynolds"><img alt="Brian Reynolds" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1508888696p2/30271885.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3372299680?book_show_action=true">Jun 03, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brian Reynolds" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brian Reynolds" href="/user/show/30271885-brian-reynolds">Brian Reynolds</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3372299680" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14604288595176999312">A pleasant, if slight, folk tale about 3 children and their travel between parents and grandparents in villages on different sides of the mountains on Christmas Eve. Most prominent are the descriptions of the places, the extensive preliminary family background - extensive enough to warrant a story line longer than 76 pages, and the exploration of what it means to be part of a village community.<br/>While some comments indicate a lack of enjoyment of the fable-like tone, I enjoyed it, as it was what I</span>
  <span id="freeText14604288595176999312" style="display:none">A pleasant, if slight, folk tale about 3 children and their travel between parents and grandparents in villages on different sides of the mountains on Christmas Eve. Most prominent are the descriptions of the places, the extensive preliminary family background - extensive enough to warrant a story line longer than 76 pages, and the exploration of what it means to be part of a village community.<br />While some comments indicate a lack of enjoyment of the fable-like tone, I enjoyed it, as it was what I expect from a tale that starts with the story of a shoemaker, a dyer and the dyer's daughter. More helpful are the comments that warn off reading the Introduction as containing spoilers. I was thankful I avoided reading it as there was a slightly suspenseful aspect to the story that I could have been spoiled. Sometimes ignorance is bliss.<br />I enjoyed reading this book, its tone and its descriptions of people and places. My only regret is the timing of reading this, as this atmospheric tale that can be read in less than 2 hours would be a good candidate for my annual Christmas Eve read. </span>
  <a data-text-id="14604288595176999312" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

